<paragraph id="5B093630FFC8EF78C4F5FDCCFB95FD4C" blockId="11.[151,1436,618,823]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
This species is remarkable in having a well-developed craspedum on abdominal tergites II–VIII. The posterior margins of the craspedum have a row of small microtrichia (
<figureCitation id="C38D2AB5FFC8EF78C726FD28FC39FD04" box="[836,922,654,678]" captionStart="FIGURES 40 – 49" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1607,1630]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,203,1585]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,193,1586]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 40 – 49. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. australis sp. n. female 40, 42 – 44, 46 – 49: 40. Dorsal view; 42. Antenna; 43. Antennal segments III – IV; 44. Abdominal tergites IV – VI; 46. Mesonotum and metanotum; 47. Abdominal tergites I – VI; 48. Abdominal sternites II – VI; 49. Head and pronotum. H. marginatus female 41, 45: 41. Dorsal view; 45. Abdominal tergites IV – V." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280416/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Fig. 
<number id="ED7E2417FFC8EF78C718FD28FC39FD04" box="[890,922,654,678]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="45.0">45</number>
</figureCitation>
). The fore wing are uniformly dark (
<figureCitation id="C38D2AB5FFC8EF78C158FD28FA2DFD04" box="[1338,1422,654,678]" captionStart="FIGURES 40 – 49" captionStartId="9.[151,264,1607,1630]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,203,1585]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[151,1436,193,1586]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURES 40 – 49. Brazilian Heterothrips. H. australis sp. n. female 40, 42 – 44, 46 – 49: 40. Dorsal view; 42. Antenna; 43. Antennal segments III – IV; 44. Abdominal tergites IV – VI; 46. Mesonotum and metanotum; 47. Abdominal tergites I – VI; 48. Abdominal sternites II – VI; 49. Head and pronotum. H. marginatus female 41, 45: 41. Dorsal view; 45. Abdominal tergites IV – V." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/280416/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
Fig. 
<number id="ED7E2417FFC8EF78C112FD28FA2DFD04" box="[1392,1422,654,678]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="41.0">41</number>
</figureCitation>
), and abdominal sternites lack of discal setae. Males have small transverse pore plates on abdominal sternites III– VIII. This species is also recorded from La Pampa, 
<collectingCountry id="23A176A0FFC8EF78C6BAFD70FCEBFD4C" box="[728,840,726,750]" name="Argentina" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Argentina</collectingCountry>
by 
<bibRefCitation id="3F274BC1FFC8EF78C713FD71FB91FD4C" box="[881,1074,726,750]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refString="De Santis, L. (1959) Adiciones a la fauna Argentina de Tisanopteros II. Acta Zoologica Lilloana, 17, 87 - 93." type="journal article">
De Santis (
<number id="ED7E2417FFC8EF78C78FFD70FB89FD4C" box="[1005,1066,726,750]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" value="1959.0">1959</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
